In 2018 , a paper was released that laid the foundation of world model. I will tell you how it works.

A world model is basically a combinations of three neural networks.

A vision Model + Memory Model + Controller Model.

The role of vision model is to look at an image and compress it into a single vector that represents whats happening in that image. A image, with 64*64 pixel, could be compressed into a vector of say 8 numbers or something. This vector is  as a latent representation of that image. So it is known as latent vector. 
Once the model is learned, using jsut this vector, we will be able to reconstruct the original image.

This is something that is actually used in youtube and all you know.. video files are largle files so when we play a video, we recieve a compressed version which is uncompressed after reaching our laptop.

now the important thing of latent vector is that, since it is small, it is forced to study the important patterns that it needs to recognize to understand the image. for example, if we are building a world model for self-driving cars, the latent vector pritozies concepts like" there is a red car in the bottom left"  rather than trying to observe the shape of the cliud. (this learning happens automatically during training, as it tries to find the best pattern to so as to drive the care without crashing)...

so this is the first model. the input is an image, and the output is a  latent vector.
 

 This vision model is known as a VAE. It has two parts, an encoder and decoder. the encoder takes an immage 64*64*3 and squeezes it down into a latent vector called z. In the original paper, it had only 32 or 64 dim.

The decoder..it takes that tiny vector z, and then tries to reconstruct the original image.


By forcing the network to squeeze the image into a tiny vector and then recreate it, the network is forced to learn what actually matters. It stops caring about individual pixels and starts "understanding" concepts like "there is a red car in the bottom left" or "the track curves to the right."

Now the second model, is the memory + prediction layer. 

Our first model allowed us to see. If we see a snapshot of a ball in the air, we cant determine if its falling or rising..for that, we need memory.

So we use a model called Recurrent Neural Netowkrs. It takes as input the current vision( latent vector zt), and the action our AI agent just took (at)...It then updates its memory(ht) to predict what the next vision (zt+1) would look like.


Now there is one special property of this model.

you see, most neural network trys to predict a single outcome which is usually the average. But the world is random.

if the car reaches a fork in the road, it might go left or right. if a model, predicts the "average",it will predict the car goes straight into the wall.

So our model dosent predict one z. it predicts a probablity distrubtion which is known as "Mixture of Gaussians". It says that ."There is a 50% chance the next frame looks like $A$, and a 50% chance it looks like $B$.".

So for this reason, our memory layer is called MDN-RNN which stands for Mixture Density Netwrok-Recurrent Neural Network.

By combining the RNN and the MDN, the agent basically builds a physics engine in its head. It learns how the environment reacts to its actions without ever being told the rules of the game. It just observes: "When I turn the wheel left ($a_t$), the vision ($z$) usually shifts to the right in the next frame."



Now suppose your playing Doom. You see a monster, and that monster now hides under a pillar. Now you dont see the monster. If you just used the VAE...you wont be seeing any monster..but this memory layer, enabled to to understand that there is a monster hiding there.

Standard RNN: Predicts the pedestrian stays on the sidewalk because that’s the "average" behavior.

MDN-RNN: Predicts a 95% chance they stay on the sidewalk and a 5% chance they jump into the road.

By predicting the distribution rather than just the average, the agent’s internal "World Model" can account for rare but high-stakes events.



Vision (V): Compresses high-dimensional sensory input (like pixels) into a small latent vector $z$.Memory (M): Predicts the next latent vector based on historical data (the "predictive" or "dreaming" part).Controller (C): Maps the outputs of V and M to a specific action.


the Controller is the decision-making component. If the other parts of the system handle "seeing" and "dreaming," the Controller handles "acting."


