Up to this point, we've talked about how the agent sees and remembers. But normally, an agent has to play the actual game millions of times to get good. This is slow and computationally "expensive."The authors asked: "If the agent has a World Model that can predict the future, why not just let it practice inside its own head?"Concept 5: The "Hallucinated" EnvironmentIn the VizDoom experiment, they stop using the actual game engine entirely. Instead, they create a loop where the agent only interacts with its own M (Memory) and V (Vision) models.The "Dream" Loop (Bit-by-Bit):The Start: The agent is given a starting "thought" (a random $z_0$).The Action: The Controller (C) looks at that thought and decides to move ($a_t$).The Hallucination: Instead of sending that move to the game, it sends it to the MDN-RNN (M).The Next Frame: The RNN "imagines" what the next vision ($z_{t+1}$) and the next reward (survival) will be, based on its internal probability math.The Repeat: The agent takes that "imagined" frame and decides its next move.
